      <h3>Improving the efficiency of phosphate fertiliser use in P fixing soils in Sub- Saharan Africa.</h3>
      <p>Rothamsted workers: Phil Brookes and Sharon Fortune.</p>
      <p>Collaborators: Dr. George Ayaga, Kenyan Agricultural Research Institute (KARI), Nairobi, Kenya. Ms. Frances Amulen, Pallisa farmers Group (PAIDA).</p>
      <p>Funders: British Council, BBSRC, KARI.</p>
      <p><img src="images/africa3%20200w.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="131"><img src="images/africa1%20200w.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="130"> </p>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <p>&nbsp;</p>
      <h2>Background to project:</h2>
      <p>Phosphorus (P) has been termed the bottleneck of world hunger. The P supply to crops can only be increased from inputs such as manures, rock phosphate or mineral fertilisers - scarce and expensive materials in Sub-Saharan Africa. Additionally, many African soils have high P fixation capacities. Consequently, large amounts of inorganic fertilizer P must be applied to correct crop P deficiency and obtain reasonable yields - impossible for impoverished smallholders. We are testing if at combinations of small quantities of inorganic fertilisers and organic manures have advantages over either applied singly in P-fixing African soils. </p>
      <h2><img src="images/africa2%20200w.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="126">Approach</h2>
      <p>We have confirmed this, obtaining significantly larger maize grain yields from this approach. We have found significant correlations between maize grain yields and soil microbial biomass P in Kenyan agricultural soils. The biomass appears to act as a natural 'slow release' fertilizer, preventing P fixation but releasing P during biomass turnover. Our results indicate, for the first time, a direct benefit to the crop from enhanced P cycling through the soil microbial biomass. We are currently conducting farmer participatory trials with small scale farmers in Kenya, using this approach.      </p>
